  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done by disguising the origins of the money, often through complex financial transactions.\n\n**In China**, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2007. The law requires financial institutions and other relevant entities to establish and implement internal controls to prevent money laundering activities, report suspicious transactions, and cooperate with law enforcement agencies. Violations of anti-money laundering laws in China can result in severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment.\n\n**Globally**, money laundering is also recognized as a criminal offense. Many countries have enacted legislation and participate in international efforts, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. The FATF sets international standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally regarded as an illegal activity, and there are robust legal frameworks in place to detect, prevent, and punish such activities.",
